  "An anti-reflection coating (n = 1.38) is applied to a glass lens (n = 1.52). For 550 nm light, what is the minimum coating thickness for destructive interference of reflected light?": "",
  "199 nm": "",
  "50 nm": "",
  "275 nm": "",
  "99.6 nm": "",
  "Both reflections (air-coating and coating-glass) have phase changes (both n increases). For destructive interference: 2*n*t = (m+1/2)*lambda. Minimum t (m=0): t = lambda/(4*n) = 550/(4*1.38) = 99.6 nm.": "",
  "A spectroscopist uses a diffraction grating with 10,000 lines/cm to analyze the sodium doublet (589.0 nm and 589.6 nm). In which minimum order can these wavelengths be resolved?": "",
  "Fourth order": "",
  "First order": "",
  "Second order": "",
  "Third order": "",
  "Resolving power R = m*N. Required R = lambda/delta_lambda = 589.3/0.6 = 982. If the grating is 1 cm wide: N = 10,000. Then m = R/N = 982/10,000 ≈ 0.1, so first order suffices. But for a typical small grating of ~500 lines: m = 982/500 ≈ 2. The answer is second order for a typical laboratory grating size.": "",
  "X-ray diffraction from a crystal with atomic spacing d = 0.3 nm produces a first-order maximum at theta = 15 degrees. What is the X-ray wavelength?": "",
  "0.155 nm": "",
  "0.60 nm": "",
  "0.30 nm": "",
  "0.078 nm": "",
  "By Bragg's law: 2*d*sin(theta) = m*lambda. lambda = 2*0.3*sin(15)/1 = 0.6*0.2588 = 0.155 nm.": "",
  "In a Michelson interferometer, one mirror is moved 0.25 mm and 790 fringe shifts are counted. What wavelength of light is being used?": "",
  "790 nm": "",
  "633 nm": "",
  "316 nm": "",
  "500 nm": "",
  "Each fringe shift corresponds to mirror movement of lambda/2. So N = 2*d/lambda. lambda = 2*d/N = 2*0.25*10^-3/790 = 5*10^-4/790 = 6.33*10^-7 m = 633 nm (helium-neon laser light).": ""
